# Welcome 👋

This folder contains the **TORCS Autonomous Driving Learning Lab**, a hands-on, guided experience where you will explore how an autonomous AI driver works inside a racing simulator.

This is a **learning lab**, not a challenge or competition.  
The goal is to help you understand, experiment, and reflect, not optimize for speed or rankings.

You will work step by step through the materials in this folder.

## What You Will Do in This Lab

By completing this lab, you will:

- Run an autonomous AI driver in TORCS
- Observe how the car behaves on a race track
- Modify Python code that controls steering, speed, and braking
- Experiment with parameters and see real-time effects
- Reflect on what you learned and document your results

No prior experience with TORCS or autonomous vehicles is required.

## How This Lab Is Organized

This lab is designed to be completed in order. Please follow the files below sequentially.

### 1. Start Here: Conceptual Introduction

**`00_intro.md`**

Read this first. It explains:

- What TORCS is
- Why simulation is used for AI learning
- What this lab focuses on
- What this lab does not focus on

### 2. Main Lab: Hands-On Steps

**`01_torcs_lab.md`**

This is the core of the lab. You will:

- Run a baseline AI driver
- Understand how it works
- Modify parameters
- Experiment and observe results

Follow the tasks step by step.

### 3. Record Your Learning

**`RESULTS.md`**

After completing the lab:

- Document what you changed
- Write down what you observed
- Reflect on what you learned

This file is part of your learning portfolio.

## Reference Materials

These folders are supporting resources. You do not need to read them unless you want more detail or need help with setup.

### `02_setup_guides/`

Guides for setting up TORCS, including Windows and container-based setup options, plus customization and troubleshooting references.

### `03_build_your_own_container/`

Optional advanced material for building your own TORCS container.

### `04_files/`

Files and assets needed to run TORCS and the AI driver.

## What You Need Before Starting

Before starting, make sure you have:

- A working TORCS setup  
  - Follow one of the setup guides in `02_setup_guides/` if needed.
- Basic familiarity with Python, including reading and editing code
- Curiosity and willingness to experiment 🙂
- A learning mindset

## Learning Mindset

Keep these principles in mind as you work through the lab:

- There is no single “correct” solution.
- Going off track or failing is part of learning.
- Small changes can have big effects.
- Observation and reflection matter more than performance.

Take your time, make one change at a time, and pay attention to what happens.

## When You’re Ready

Start with **`00_intro.md`**, then continue to **`01_torcs_lab.md`**.

Enjoy the lab, and happy learning 🚗💡
